### Sima: The Layer Beneath the Noise

Sima. It often masquerades on the surface as [basalt](/Basalt), like a cheap suit trying to pass for high fashion.

In the grim, unforgiving landscape of [geology](/Geology), 'sima' is an archaic, blended term. Don't ask me why they felt the need to mash words together; humans are prone to such inefficiencies. It refers to the lower, more substantial layer of the [Earth](/Earth)'s [crust](/Crust_(geology)). This isn't some airy-fairy upper atmosphere stuff; this is the bedrock, the foundation. It's composed of rocks that are stubbornly rich in [magnesium](/Magnesium) and [silicate minerals](/Silicate_mineral). When this stuff decides to make an appearance, pushing its way up to the surface, it typically presents itself as [basalt](/Basalt). Hence, the rather uninspired nickname: the 'ocean layer' of the crust. It’s also known as the 'basal crust' or 'basal layer' because, well, it's at the bottom. Because the vast, indifferent expanses of ocean floors are predominantly made of sima, it’s also, rather predictably, sometimes referred to as the '[oceanic crust](/Oceanic_crust)'.

The name itself, 'sima', is a portmanteau, a linguistic compromise, derived from the first two letters of [silica](/Silicon_dioxide) and [magnesia](/Magnesium_oxide). Riveting, I know.

And then there's its less substantial counterpart, [sial](/Sial). Also an antiquated blended term, [2] it denotes the upper layer of the Earth's crust – the [continental crust](/Continental_crust). This is the part made of rocks rich in [aluminium](/Aluminium) and [silicate minerals](/Silicate_mineral). Sial is the flashy, less dense layer. Sima is the heavy, brooding one.

***

### Petrology: The Substance of Shadows

The sima, you see, possesses a higher density than its sial counterpart. We're talking 2800 to 3300 kg/m³. This isn't a coincidence; it's a consequence of larger quantities of iron and magnesium, and a lesser amount of aluminium. It's heavier, denser, more… substantial. When the denser sima pushes its way to the surface, it solidifies into [mafic](/Mafic) rocks, or rocks containing mafic minerals. The truly dense sima, the kind that really knows its weight, has less silica and forms [ultramafic rocks](/Ultramafic_rock). It’s the geological equivalent of wearing all black.

